(this["webpackJsonppersonal-site"]=this["webpackJsonppersonal-site"]||[]).push([[8],{169:function(e,t,a){"use strict";a.r(t),a.d(t,"default",(function(){return n}));var s=a(0),o=(a(1),a(11)),r=a.p+"static/media/TakeMe.bbad35cb.gif",i=a.p+"static/media/frantic-studying.32f06f1f.gif";function n(){var e={display:"flex",justifyContent:"center",alignItems:"center"};return Object(s.jsx)(o.a,{title:"Stats",description:"Some statistics about Michael D'Angelo and mldangelo.com",children:Object(s.jsxs)("article",{className:"post",id:"stats",children:[Object(s.jsx)("header",{children:Object(s.jsx)("div",{className:"title",children:Object(s.jsx)("h2",{"data-testid":"heading",children:"My First Year as an Undergraduate Research Assistant"})})}),Object(s.jsx)("p",{children:"I knew I wanted to get involved in research at the University of Kansas. However, it was already the end of my junior year and I had no knowledge of any computer science research labs. Choice overload was sinking in and I knew I had to take action fast. So what did I think of? Email every computer science professor!"}),Object(s.jsx)("div",{style:e,children:Object(s.jsx)("img",{src:r,alt:"Logo"})}),Object(s.jsx)("p",{children:"Yes this was my plan, to email random professors. I had my eyes set one professor in the department, however, he never responded to my email. I was offended, but it was expected since it was a very random email. However, I was in this professors class and knew that there was a way I could talk to him where he could not escape, office hours. So I asked him about his research there and while he did speak about what he did, he had no openings."}),Object(s.jsx)("p",{children:"Finally, a professor responded. He said he would be delighted to hop on a zoom call and share what he does for research. I was thrilled, someone not only responded, but wanted to chat! During the call he spoke about his research interests which involved applying machine learning to medical problems, specifically hearing aids. After he explained what he, did he offered me a position as a research assistant and I accepted."}),Object(s.jsx)("p",{children:"However, he explained that this position as a reserach assistant was a bit different from normal ones. First off, it was only the professor and I doing research. No one else was on the team. Secondly, the reserach was self guided. This meant that at the begenning he gave me about a 100 research papers to read on the subject, and after I read those it would be up to be to figure out the next step. It scared me a lot at first knowing that a majority of the reserach would be my responsibility. Despite that worry I marched ahead."}),Object(s.jsx)("p",{children:"However, he explained that this position as a reserach assistant was a bit different from normal ones. First off, it was only the professor and I doing research. No one else was on the team. Secondly, the reserach was self guided. This meant that at the begenning he gave me about a 100 research papers to read on the subject, and after I read those it would be up to be to figure out the next step. It scared me a lot at first knowing that a majority of the research would be my responsibility. Despite that worry I marched ahead."}),Object(s.jsx)("div",{style:e,children:Object(s.jsx)("img",{src:i,style:{height:"290px"},alt:"Logo"})}),Object(s.jsx)("p",{children:"I first started reading those research papers in April of 2021. It is now June of 2022 and I am happy that everything worked out the way it did. First off, this self guided reserach was a blessing in disguise! Over the course of the year I eventually finished all the papers. First, a big takeaway from that experience was to rewire my mind to understand that academic papers are not like articles you can just read, you have to take time to read it, understand it, and reread it multiple times to understand what is saying. Secondly, I learned how to plan ahead. The end goal of doing this research was to write a paper. Writing a paper is a big endeavor and to accomplish this I needed to have steps that I could follow and execute. One way I did this was by simply taking notes of my thoughts. After every research paper I would document not only what the paper was talking about, but my thoughts about the paper. Every paper addresses a problem to something and a solution to that problem. After reading enough papers I started to pick up on common problems and all the notes I took solidified that these were common problems."}),Object(s.jsx)("p",{children:"I could fill up a book with everything I learned my first year, however this post was just to give a brief overview on how everything went. There were many highs I experienced over the year and there were also many lows. The most important thing I learned was to keep moving forward. Even if you do not know the solution currently, if you keep working at it, it will eventually come!"})]})})}}}]);
